=You are writing Follow Up 1 for a cold email sequence to a recruitment agency. The pitch has already been sent with no reply.

INPUTS:
- Client first name: {{ $('Get row(s) in sheet1').first().json.first_name }}
- Company name: {{ $('Get row(s) in sheet1').first().json.name }}
- Website: {{ $('Get row(s) in sheet1').first().json.website }}
- Website problem: {{ $('Get row(s) in sheet1').first().json.website_problem }}
- Specific issues (pipe-separated): {{ $('Get row(s) in sheet1').first().json.recognizable_reason }}
- Consequence: {{ $('Get row(s) in sheet1').first().json.consequence_mechanics }}
- Sender name: {{ $('Edit Fields').first().json.your_name }}
- Pitch email: {{ $('pitch parsed').first().json.subject }} {{ $('pitch parsed').first().json.body }}

TASK:
Stay on the exact same single issue from the pitch. Do not switch topics, do not introduce a second issue, do not generalise. Sharpen the consequence — show what is actually happening to the business because of this one issue, from a fresh angle that wasn't used in the pitch.

RULES:
- Do NOT copy or repeat any wording from the pitch
- Do NOT reference, summarise, or mention "the pitch" or any previous email
- Do NOT say "just following up", "circling back", "checking in", or any line that is about you rather than the visitor
- Do NOT use corporate filler words: mockup, demo, optimise, streamline, leverage, innovative, solution, enhance, seamlessly, or similar
- Do NOT use brochure phrases: creates friction, impacts revenue, missed opportunities, poor first impression, or similar
- Do NOT use hedging words: could, might, may, potentially, possibly, some, many, or similar
- Never assume where the visitor goes after leaving — just say they leave
- Subject line must be different to the pitch subject line, and specific to the issue
- Under 70 words total (body only, not counting subject)
- Subject line: exactly 3 or 4 words
- Plain business voice, sound natural and human
- Structure: one sentence sharpening the consequence of the same issue from a new angle → one sentence on what that means for the business → CTA
- CTA must use different wording to the pitch CTA — use: "Want me to send it over?"
- Sign off: Best, [sender name]

OUTPUT:
Return only valid JSON in this exact format, nothing else, no markdown, no explanation:
{"subject": "...", "body": "..."}

parameters.jsCode:
const raw = items[0].json.content.parts[0].text;
const parsed = JSON.parse(raw);

return [{
  json: {
    subject: parsed.subject,
    body: parsed.body
  }
}];

